00:30:29.656 --> 00:30:33.616
Florida, and Shahin at Cornell, where they take immortalized stromal

512
00:30:33.696 --> 00:30:37.596
cells that in many cases have a mirusta-lated AKT, which then you

513
00:30:37.636 --> 00:30:40.236
can take primary cells and culture them ex vivo.

514
00:30:40.576 --> 00:30:43.856
And if you were to, after weeks in culture, put them back in a mouse, they can

515
00:30:44.236 --> 00:30:48.092
recapitulate that culture.And so for us, that was

516
00:30:48.172 --> 00:30:52.072
great for a couple reasons. The first is that we were able to take that system, and

517
00:30:52.132 --> 00:30:56.012
as I like to say, a rotation student in our lab can take the system

518
00:30:56.032 --> 00:30:59.832
and grow primary stem cells in their first three days of their rotation, and we've

519
00:30:59.872 --> 00:31:03.732
been able to, with Jason and Shahin's help, teach many other labs how to

520
00:31:03.792 --> 00:31:07.372
use that system. But the critical thing for us is that really was a

521
00:31:07.412 --> 00:31:11.162
platform. And so what we wanted to do was take this platform that Shahin and

522
00:31:11.232 --> 00:31:14.612
Jason developed and use it as a perturbation system.

523
00:31:14.952 --> 00:31:17.992
And so what we did really, thanks to the work of Michael Wartz,

524
00:31:18.572 --> 00:31:21.882
was take primary stem cells, mutant or wild type,

525
00:31:22.452 --> 00:31:26.292
and basically either do chemical perturbations or CRISPR perturbations, which would

526
00:31:26.332 --> 00:31:29.832
allow us to look for things that might either deplete or enhance the

527
00:31:29.872 --> 00:31:32.092
fitness of mutant versus wild-type stem cells.

528
00:31:32.562 --> 00:31:36.072
And Mike actually was able to optimize this, that we can get anywhere from 50% to

529
00:31:36.252 --> 00:31:40.132
80% editing with a lentiviral-induced CRISPR guide in

530
00:31:40.212 --> 00:31:43.752
primary stem cells. And we can either use Cas9 mice or deliver

531
00:31:43.792 --> 00:31:47.772
Cas9 with electroporation. I won't talk today, but we actually think

532
00:31:47.792 --> 00:31:51.551
lipid nanoparticles delivery is going to be even better in these ex vivo

533
00:31:51.592 --> 00:31:52.911
systems than viral delivery.

534
00:31:53.932 --> 00:31:57.862
And so what this allows us to do is to take primary stem cells and

535
00:31:57.892 --> 00:31:59.812
to screen against a library of targets.

536
00:32:00.272 --> 00:32:04.012
You can't do genome-wide CRISPR screens because at least the math,

537
00:32:04.432 --> 00:32:08.252
if you're getting hundreds or thousands of stem cells from an individual mouse or

538
00:32:08.392 --> 00:32:12.372
pool of mice, you're not going to get representation across 20,000 genes and five

539
00:32:12.452 --> 00:32:16.232
guides per gene. So the strategy we've used is to do library-based screens

540
00:32:16.412 --> 00:32:20.232
of genes of interest, whether it's kino-based screens or epigenome-based

541
00:32:20.292 --> 00:32:22.032
screens or inflammation-based screens.

542
00:32:23.022 --> 00:32:25.272
And so Mike's first screen was relatively simple.

543
00:32:25.662 --> 00:32:28.992
He took mutant or wild type cells for different CH alleles,

544
00:32:29.112 --> 00:32:32.622
Tet2, DNMT3A, IDH1,

545
00:32:32.712 --> 00:32:36.632
IDH2, and a CRISPR library into either

546
00:32:36.672 --> 00:32:39.852
wild type or mutant stem cells, and looked for things that would selectively

547
00:32:39.912 --> 00:32:43.852
deplete mutant stem cells and not deplete wild-type stem cells.

548
00:32:44.292 --> 00:32:48.132
What's nice about these culture systems is we can harvest at different time

549
00:32:48.212 --> 00:32:51.812
points in the culture and monitor depletion over time, and you can actually

550
00:32:51.872 --> 00:32:54.532
isolate different populations. You can look for things that deplete

551
00:32:56.012 --> 00:32:59.692
the whole population, things that selectively deplete in the more immature, or

552
00:32:59.732 --> 00:33:02.812
things that might deplete in the mature population, such that you might, for

553
00:33:02.852 --> 00:33:04.292
example, block differentiation.

554
00:33:04.332 --> 00:33:06.772
So you get different readouts depending on how you do the screen.

555
00:33:07.632 --> 00:33:10.172
And in Mike's work, which is published, which is just the

556
00:33:13.172 --> 00:33:16.252
foreshadowing to the work which will be unpublished, which I'll show from this

557
00:33:16.272 --> 00:33:20.092
slide, he was able to show that we found a new dependency in

558
00:33:20.132 --> 00:33:24.112
Tet and IDH mutant leukemias, which was in KDM3B.

559
00:33:24.832 --> 00:33:28.732
And in fact, this was selective to Tet and IDH, and it was true ex vivo.

560
00:33:29.172 --> 00:33:32.952
It was true in vivo, and I won't take you through the mechanism, but refer you to

561
00:33:32.992 --> 00:33:36.962
his paper that we're able to delineate a relationship between

562
00:33:37.032 --> 00:33:40.592
this epigenetic regulator and the regulation of different genes, including the

563
00:33:40.612 --> 00:33:42.612
thrombopoietin receptor, MPL.

564
00:33:43.892 --> 00:33:47.632
And so that really has allowed my lab to embark now on functional genomic

565
00:33:47.752 --> 00:33:51.042
screens alone in collaboration with many groups in different

566
00:33:51.372 --> 00:33:55.292
contexts. And so the one we really wanted to turn to was a

567
00:33:55.302 --> 00:33:56.772
disease that we've thought a lot about

568
00:33:57.652 --> 00:34:01.452
over the last couple of years, which is IDH-mutated AML, and

569
00:34:01.532 --> 00:34:05.332
ask if we could identify mutant-specific dependencies in this context.

570
00:34:05.932 --> 00:34:09.783
And it wasn't lost on us and many others that thanks to lots of work from many

571
00:34:10.112 --> 00:34:14.053
colleagues in academia, as well as at Agios, and Celgene

572
00:34:14.092 --> 00:34:17.432
and Cervie, we now have approved drugs for both

573
00:34:17.533 --> 00:34:21.243
IDH1 and IDH2 that block the neomorphic functionality of

574
00:34:21.312 --> 00:34:25.243
those mutations. Although those drugs are active with

575
00:34:25.292 --> 00:34:29.092
about 20% to 30% complete response rates and probably

576
00:34:29.192 --> 00:34:33.102
aggregate benefits of greater than 50%, they are not

577
00:34:33.112 --> 00:34:35.602
by any means curative or definitive as monotherapy.

578
00:34:35.701 --> 00:34:39.533
Although I'll point out that the IDH1 inhibitor combined with azacitidine is

579
00:34:39.632 --> 00:34:43.312
quite active in newly diagnosed IDH1-mutated AML.

580
00:34:44.392 --> 00:34:47.592
But our challenge was that there are certain genetic subtypes of

581
00:34:47.632 --> 00:34:50.412
IDH-mutated leukemia that really don't respond well at all.

582
00:34:51.072 --> 00:34:54.872
And in a correlative science paper that my lab did in collaboration with our

583
00:34:54.912 --> 00:34:58.872
colleagues at Agios, we showed a number of years ago that patients that

584
00:34:58.892 --> 00:35:02.772
have IDH-mutated leukemia, that have co-mutations in NRAS

585
00:35:02.912 --> 00:35:06.731
or PTPN11 most commonly, but anything in the RAS map kinase

586
00:35:06.772 --> 00:35:09.792
pathway, don't respond to IDH inhibition.

587
00:35:09.852 --> 00:35:13.522
This has been borne out in a number of studies, and really for us is

588
00:35:13.552 --> 00:35:17.132
vexing because that means that there's a subset of patients with IDH-mutated

589
00:35:17.152 --> 00:35:20.252
leukemia that have this a priori lack of

590
00:35:20.612 --> 00:35:24.352
responsiveness biomarker. And so that really has allowed us to

591
00:35:24.452 --> 00:35:28.152
ask a fundamental question, which was, could we understand two things?

592
00:35:28.252 --> 00:35:31.752
One is what's the mechanism that underlies that resistance?

593
00:35:31.872 --> 00:35:33.432
I will say that's a work in progress.

594
00:35:33.812 --> 00:35:37.332
And the second is, are there unique dependencies in those

595
00:35:37.352 --> 00:35:39.452
leukemias that have IDH and RAS together?

596
00:35:40.032 --> 00:35:43.932
So Becca Gilford, who's an MSTP student in the lab, has taken

597
00:35:43.952 --> 00:35:47.672
this on, and all the work I'll show you today is her work, and she's

598
00:35:47.732 --> 00:35:51.712
taken a bifurcated strategy. The first is

599
00:35:51.772 --> 00:35:54.512
that we've developed a set of genetically engineered mouse models.

600
00:35:54.572 --> 00:35:57.992
Now, the challenge here is that you need leukemias that are

601
00:35:58.072 --> 00:36:01.672
AML with or without RAS, and IDH1 or IDH2 by

602
00:36:01.712 --> 00:36:03.232
themselves don't cause leukemia.

603
00:36:03.632 --> 00:36:07.352
So we basically generated IDH MPML double mutant leukemias

604
00:36:07.652 --> 00:36:10.552
that did or did not have oncogenic NRAS.

605
00:36:11.172 --> 00:36:14.592
And then we developed a set of human models, all in graftable

606
00:36:14.612 --> 00:36:18.332
PDXs, that had the same sort of with and without RAS.

607
00:36:18.432 --> 00:36:22.372
And this allows us to both study in the functional genomic studies in

608
00:36:22.412 --> 00:36:26.172
the mouse and then begin to validate those pathways in human, which is

609
00:36:26.192 --> 00:36:28.772
obviously of important translational consequence.

610
00:36:29.772 --> 00:36:33.522
And so what we were able to show in the genetically engineered mouse model

