00:38:28.956 --> 00:38:32.656
some myeloid maturation, don't budge. They stay exactly where they are.

643
00:38:32.996 --> 00:38:36.716
And that correlates with the clinical observation that they both don't benefit

644
00:38:37.036 --> 00:38:40.816
with respect to response, and in this case, differentiation is

645
00:38:40.896 --> 00:38:43.716
correlated in the human with efficacy.

646
00:38:43.756 --> 00:38:47.516
We don't know if you need to differentiate to get the response

647
00:38:47.896 --> 00:38:51.836
or it's a parallel marker of response, but it is an important

648
00:38:51.876 --> 00:38:55.816
thing. So this led us on a little bit of a tangent, which is, can

649
00:38:55.856 --> 00:38:59.736
we develop strategies now to target these recalcitrant, difficult to

650
00:38:59.876 --> 00:39:02.236
treat, difficult to differentiate leukemias?

651
00:39:02.965 --> 00:39:06.836
And so what Rebecca did was go back to the lab and take

652
00:39:06.845 --> 00:39:10.465
those isogenic systems, so basically taking either wild-type stem cells,

653
00:39:11.036 --> 00:39:14.596
IDH MPML double mutant AML cells, or the triple mutant

654
00:39:14.616 --> 00:39:18.036
cells that are oncogenic NRAS, and using that stromal co-culture

655
00:39:18.216 --> 00:39:20.856
system, basically do a CRISPR-based library.

656
00:39:21.216 --> 00:39:24.936
And we used a version of a RAS-directed library that David

657
00:39:24.976 --> 00:39:28.916
Sabatini and folks at the Broad had developed years ago, and we both

658
00:39:29.116 --> 00:39:32.876
curated it to only look at genes that were expressed in primary human

659
00:39:32.916 --> 00:39:36.736
AML cells from that library, and we added some other signaling effectors that we

660
00:39:36.756 --> 00:39:40.166
thought might be of interest. One important point here is

661
00:39:40.196 --> 00:39:43.676
that the AML cells, just like the clonal

