00:39:50.736 --> 00:39:54.676
leukemogenic capacity. So these cultures do allow us to keep

665
00:39:54.956 --> 00:39:58.936
primary leukemia cells alive ex vivo and retain, we think, the

666
00:39:59.036 --> 00:40:01.916
key features that drive in vivo leukemogenesis.

667
00:40:02.936 --> 00:40:06.856
And so we did this screen in NRAS mutant leukemias.

668
00:40:07.156 --> 00:40:10.836
We compared this both to wild-type stem cells and to the

669
00:40:10.896 --> 00:40:12.956
leukemia cells that were RAS wild type.

670
00:40:13.496 --> 00:40:15.656
And if you do the comparison either way, you get two things.

671
00:40:15.696 --> 00:40:19.516
The first is NRAS came out as a dependency only in the NRAS

672
00:40:19.556 --> 00:40:23.185
mutated cells. That's a good sanity check that we're getting biology that you'd

673
00:40:23.236 --> 00:40:26.876
predict to be true. But the other thing that was intriguing to us was that we

674
00:40:26.916 --> 00:40:30.616
pulled out a couple of genes that we honestly didn't know a lot about.

675
00:40:30.736 --> 00:40:32.666
One, which was ELOVL1 and

