00:41:40.536 --> 00:41:43.566
leukemic cells that are RAS wild type, we do not see this.

696
00:41:43.616 --> 00:41:47.516
So this dependency on ELOVL1 in our hands is specific

697
00:41:47.896 --> 00:41:50.076
to whether you have oncogenic NRAS.

698
00:41:51.796 --> 00:41:54.616
So we also have begun to try some therapeutics.

699
00:41:54.736 --> 00:41:58.676
Vertex had actually developed for neurologic diseases, an

700
00:41:58.736 --> 00:42:01.736
inhibitor of ELOVL1 for a number of storage diseases.

701
00:42:02.096 --> 00:42:06.016
And we actually can show that we get very nice depletion of the triple

702
00:42:06.076 --> 00:42:08.496
mutant cells, but not really the double mutant cells.

703
00:42:08.536 --> 00:42:12.206
And we're now doing both ex vivo treatment followed by in vivo propagation and in

704
00:42:12.276 --> 00:42:15.376
vivo treatment. These drugs are not clinically

705
00:42:15.876 --> 00:42:19.396
utilizable because they were designed to penetrate the CNS and

706
00:42:19.516 --> 00:42:22.786
actually achieve something there for those diseases.

707
00:42:23.096 --> 00:42:25.096
That turned out to be toxic in the CNS.

708
00:42:25.696 --> 00:42:29.176
But this does tell you that if you could develop an ELOVL1 inhibitor that did not

709
00:42:29.276 --> 00:42:33.196
penetrate the CNS, it might perhaps be of therapeutic import in these

710
00:42:33.236 --> 00:42:33.736
diseases.

711
00:42:34.876 --> 00:42:38.856
And so we next wanted to ask, given the genetic and pharmacologic data, if we

712
00:42:38.896 --> 00:42:40.456
could get a little bit more on a mechanism.

713
00:42:40.936 --> 00:42:44.216
So we did some add back studies, either with a full-length

